+# D.U.H. Architecture
+
+D.U.H. is a ports-and-adapters coding agent built around a small async kernel. The codebase separates four concerns:
+
+- CLI and UI entry points choose a run mode and collect operator intent.
+- The kernel owns conversation state, event flow, compaction, budgeting, and safety checks.
+- Ports define the narrow interfaces the kernel depends on.
+- Adapters implement providers, tools, persistence, approvals, renderers, and sandboxes.
+
+That split is visible in the runtime path: `duh/cli/main.py` selects print mode, REPL, TUI, SDK mode, review mode, batch mode, or bridge mode; `duh/cli/session_builder.py` assembles the session; `duh/kernel/engine.py` and `duh/kernel/loop.py` run turns; `duh/ports/` defines the contracts; and `duh/adapters/`, `duh/tools/`, `duh/providers/`, and `duh/security/` provide concrete behavior.
+
+## Top-Level Layout
+
+At a high level, the repository is organized like this:
+
+- `duh/cli/`: argument parsing, REPL, print-mode runner, session assembly, slash command dispatch, SDK runner.
+- `duh/kernel/`: message model, engine, query loop, token accounting, plan mode, snapshot mode, memory helpers, safety primitives, utility state machines.
+- `duh/ports/`: abstract interfaces for providers, tools, approvals, context compaction, renderers, memory, and session stores.
+- `duh/adapters/`: concrete provider adapters, approvers, stores, compaction adapters, native tool executor, structured logging, sandbox backends, MCP integration.
+- `duh/tools/`: concrete tools such as `Read`, `Write`, `Edit`, `Bash`, `WebFetch`, `WebSearch`, `Task`, `Memory*`, `HTTP`, `Docker`, `Database`, `GitHub`, and more.
+- `duh/providers/`: provider/model registry logic that resolves model strings and picks the adapter backend.
+- `duh/security/`: higher-level security policy, trifecta checks, findings, exceptions, audit support, and scanners.
+- `duh/ui/`: the Textual TUI.
+- `duh/bridge/`: remote bridge server support.
+
+The main assembly pattern is intentionally centralized. `SessionBuilder` wires path policy, skills, tools, hooks, MCP, provider backend, compactor, store, approver, and engine in one place. That reduces duplication between print mode and REPL, but it also means `duh/cli/session_builder.py` is the highest-leverage file when you need to understand how a session comes together.
+
+## Component Diagram
+
+```mermaid
+flowchart TD
+    A[duh.cli.main] --> B[duh.cli.parser]
+    A --> C[Runner / REPL / TUI / SDK]
+    C --> D[duh.cli.session_builder.SessionBuilder]
+    D --> E[duh.providers.registry]
+    D --> F[duh.tools.registry]
+    D --> G[duh.adapters.native_executor.NativeExecutor]
+    D --> H[Approver Adapter]
+    D --> I[duh.adapters.file_store.FileStore]
+    D --> J[duh.kernel.engine.Engine]
+
+    J --> K[duh.kernel.loop.query]
+    K --> L[Deps.call_model]
+    L --> M[Provider Adapter]
+    K --> N[Deps.approve]
+    N --> H
+    K --> O[Deps.run_tool]
+    O --> G
+    G --> P[Tool Objects]
+    K --> Q[tool_result_message]
+    Q --> J
+
+    J --> R[Session Store]
+    J --> S[Hooks / Audit / Auto-memory / Compaction]
+
+    C --> T[Renderer]
+    J --> T
+```
+
+The important design choice is that the kernel never imports a provider SDK or a concrete tool module directly. It talks to callables and protocols held in `Deps`, `EngineConfig`, and the `tools` list.
+
+## Core Runtime Objects
+
+### `Deps`
+
+`duh/kernel/deps.py` defines the dependency-injection surface the kernel consumes:
+
+- `call_model`: async generator that yields streaming provider events.
+- `run_tool`: async callable that executes a tool.
+- `approve`: async callable that authorizes tool calls.
+- `compact`: async callable that trims conversation state.
+- optional extras such as `hook_registry`, `confirm_gate`, `session_id`, and `audit_logger`.
+
+This is the central seam in the system. If you understand `Deps`, you understand how the kernel stays adapter-agnostic.
+
+### `EngineConfig`
+
+`duh/kernel/engine.py` stores per-session policy and behavior:
+
+- model and fallback model
+- system prompt
+- tool list
+- max turns and max cost
+- thinking/tool-choice settings
+- trifecta acknowledgement and auto-memory toggle
+
+`EngineConfig` is intentionally plain. The kernel reads it, but most construction choices are made earlier by `SessionBuilder`.
+
+### `Message`
+
+`duh/kernel/messages.py` defines the kernel’s lingua franca:
+
+- `Message`
+- `TextBlock`
+- `ToolUseBlock`
+- `ToolResultBlock`
+- `ThinkingBlock`
+- `ImageBlock`
+
+Provider adapters translate external SDK payloads into this internal message/block representation. Tool results also get turned back into message content blocks before the next model turn.
+
+## Stateful Subsystems
+
+The kernel keeps most state in a few focused helpers instead of a single monolithic session object.
+
+### Session History and Persistence
+
+`Engine` owns the in-memory message list, turn counters, token totals, cache tracking, and the session identifier. Persistence is delegated to the `SessionStore` port and, in the default runtime, implemented by `duh/adapters/file_store.py`. The file store writes JSONL session files per project, appends only new messages, preserves taint metadata, and uses temp-file replacement for atomicity.
+
+`SessionBuilder._maybe_resume_session()` is the bridge between persistence and runtime state. It can:
+
+- resume a specific session by ID
+- continue the latest session automatically
+- compact on resume when `--summarize` is set
+- restore coordinator mode by rewriting the system prompt prefix
+
+That means session restore is not just “load text from disk”; it also repairs higher-level session mode.
+
+### Compaction and Context Recovery
+
+Compaction is spread across several cooperating modules:
+
+- `duh/kernel/engine.py` decides when to compact
+- `duh/kernel/context_gate.py` blocks turns after compaction if the context is still too large
+- `duh/kernel/post_compact.py` can rebuild file, plan, and skill context after a shrink
+- `duh/kernel/compact_analytics.py` and `duh/kernel/cache_tracker.py` measure what happened
+
+The design goal is to keep the main loop simple while still giving the runtime a way to recover important context after aggressive trimming. This is why file tracker state, plan state, and loaded skills are treated as recoverable side channels rather than just raw message text.
+
+### Alternative Execution Modes
+
+Two kernel-adjacent modes are worth calling out because they reuse the same primitives without changing the kernel contract:
+
+- `duh/kernel/plan_mode.py` wraps an `Engine` to split work into a planning phase with `tool_choice="none"` and an execution phase with full tools.
+- `duh/kernel/snapshot.py` provides read-only and ghost-execution helpers so a caller can fork conversation state and, in ghost mode, intercept writes into an in-memory overlay before optionally merging them back to disk.
+
+These are not separate engines. They are specialized orchestration layers built on top of `Engine`, `query()`, `Message`, and the tool executor abstractions.
+
+## Data Flow: One User Request End to End
+
+This is the flow for a single print-mode request such as `duh -p "fix the bug"`:
+
+1. `duh/cli/main.py` calls `build_parser()` from `duh/cli/parser.py`, parses CLI flags, and routes to `run_print_mode()` in `duh/cli/runner.py`.
+2. `run_print_mode()` builds `SessionBuilderOptions` and creates `SessionBuilder(args, options, ...)`.
+3. `SessionBuilder.build()` resolves the provider through `SessionBuilder._build_provider()`, which delegates to `duh/providers/registry.py`:
+   - `resolve_provider_name()` chooses a provider from flags, model string, saved auth, env vars, or Ollama detection.
+   - `build_model_backend()` instantiates the concrete backend and returns a `ProviderBackend` with `call_model`.
+4. `SessionBuilder` constructs the tool set:
+   - `_build_path_policy()` builds `duh/security/path_policy.PathPolicy` from the git root.
+   - `_load_skills()` loads skills via `duh/kernel/skill.py`.
+   - `_discover_deferred_tools()` loads plugin-advertised tools for `ToolSearch`.
+   - `_build_tools()` calls `duh/tools/registry.get_all_tools(...)`.
+   - `_connect_mcp()` optionally appends `MCPToolWrapper` instances after connecting MCP servers.
+5. `SessionBuilder` constructs the system prompt:
+   - base constitution prompt
+   - optional coordinator prompt from `duh/kernel/coordinator.py`
+   - optional brief instruction
+   - repo/user instructions from config
+   - memory prompt from `duh/kernel/memory.build_memory_prompt()`
+   - environment block
+   - git context from `duh/kernel/git_context.py`
+   - skills/templates/deferred-tools hints
+6. `SessionBuilder` wires adapters:
+   - `NativeExecutor(tools=tools, cwd=...)`
+   - approver adapter (`AutoApprover`, `InteractiveApprover`, or `TieredApprover`)
+   - `SimpleCompactor`
+   - `FileStore`
+   - `Deps(call_model=..., run_tool=executor.run, approve=approver.check, compact=compactor.compact, ...)`
+7. `SessionBuilder` creates `Engine(config=EngineConfig(...), deps=deps, session_store=store, ...)`.
+8. `run_print_mode()` iterates `async for event in engine.run(args.prompt)`.
+9. Inside `Engine.run()`:
+   - `_begin_turn()` appends the user message and estimates token usage.
+   - `_emit_session_lifecycle()` fires setup/task hooks.
+   - `_auto_compact()` compacts if the context is too large.
+   - `ContextGate.check()` blocks the turn if post-compaction context is still too close to the model limit.
+   - `_run_with_ptl_retry()` drives the actual query loop.
+10. `_run_with_ptl_retry()` calls `duh/kernel/loop.query(...)`.
+11. `query()` invokes `deps.call_model(...)`, which streams events from the provider adapter.
+12. Provider events come back as kernel events:
+   - `text_delta`
+   - `thinking_delta`
+   - `assistant`
+   - eventually tool-use blocks embedded in the assistant message
+13. If the assistant message contains tool calls, `query()` executes them:
+   - it groups consecutive read-only tool calls and runs them concurrently
+   - it runs mutating tools sequentially
+   - it consults `deps.approve` before execution
+   - it optionally consults `deps.confirm_gate`
+   - it calls `deps.run_tool`
+14. In the default runtime, `deps.run_tool` is `NativeExecutor.run()`:
+   - find tool by name
+   - build `ToolContext`
+   - call tool-level `check_permissions()`
+   - snapshot pre-edit state for undo if needed
+   - call `tool.call(...)` under timeout
+   - track file operations and truncate/redact output if configured
+15. `query()` collects all tool outputs into a single `tool_result_message` user message. That is important for Anthropic compatibility and is explicitly documented in `duh/kernel/loop.py`.
+16. The loop calls the provider again with the updated message list so the model can continue from tool output.
+17. `Engine` captures assistant messages and tool result messages into session state, updates token counters, checks budgets, auto-saves through `FileStore.save()`, optionally runs auto-memory extraction, and emits usage events.
+18. The CLI runner renders events:
+   - in print mode, `text_delta` goes to stdout, tool activity goes to stderr, JSON/NDJSON modes serialize the events
+   - in REPL and TUI, renderer adapters and slash-command infrastructure sit on top of the same event stream
+
+That flow is stable across modes. REPL, TUI, and SDK mode differ mainly in assembly and rendering, not in kernel control flow.
+
+## Extension Points
+
+### Add a New Provider Adapter
+
+The provider seam is defined by `duh/ports/provider.py`:
+
+- implement `ModelProvider.stream(...)`
+- yield kernel events that match what `duh/kernel/loop.py` expects
+
+In practice, a new provider requires four changes:
+
+1. Add an adapter module under `duh/adapters/` similar to `openai.py`, `anthropic.py`, `gemini.py`, `groq.py`, `ollama.py`, or `stub_provider.py`.
+2. Make the adapter expose a `stream()` implementation compatible with `Deps.call_model`.
+3. Teach `duh/providers/registry.py` how to:
+   - infer the provider from model names if needed
+   - choose default models
+   - build the backend in `build_model_backend()`
+   - optionally enumerate models in `available_models_for_provider()`
+4. If you want CLI auto-selection, ensure `resolve_provider_name()` can discover the provider from auth state, env vars, or model prefixes.
+
+The default runtime never imports provider adapters directly from the kernel. The only place that knows the concrete adapter class is the registry and session builder layer.
+
+### Add a New Tool
+
+There are two ways to add a tool: runtime registration and permanent product registration.
+
+The tool contract lives in `duh/kernel/tool.py`:
+
+- provide `name`, `description`, and `input_schema`
+- implement `async def call(self, input, context) -> ToolResult`
+- optionally expose `is_read_only`, `is_destructive`, and `check_permissions()`
+
+For one-off or embedded use, register the tool at runtime with `NativeExecutor.register()` or pass it in the initial tool list. That is the path used in the tutorial.
+
+For a first-class built-in tool:
+
+1. Add a module under `duh/tools/`.
+2. Instantiate it from `duh/tools/registry.py:get_all_tools()`.
+3. If tiered approvals or snapshot mode should understand it, classify it in `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`.
+4. If it contributes session capabilities, set a `capabilities` flag so `duh/security/trifecta.py` can account for it.
+5. If it needs filesystem boundaries or model context information, read them from `ToolContext` and/or accept `path_policy` in the constructor like `ReadTool`, `WriteTool`, `EditTool`, and `MultiEditTool`.
+
+The subtle but important point is that approvals are not inferred from `is_read_only`. The concurrent execution path in `query()` uses `is_read_only`, but tiered approval logic uses `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`. If you skip that classification, `TieredApprover` treats the tool conservatively as unknown.
+
+### Add a New Slash Command
+
+Slash commands are centralized in `duh/cli/slash_commands.py`. To add one:
+
+1. Add a handler method on `SlashDispatcher`.
+2. Register it in `SlashDispatcher._HANDLERS`.
+3. If the command must run in an already-running event loop, also add an async version to `_ASYNC_HANDLERS`.
+4. Add help text to `SLASH_COMMANDS`.
+
+The REPL imports `SLASH_COMMANDS` from that module, and the TUI uses the same dispatcher through `async_dispatch()`. That keeps REPL and TUI slash behavior aligned.
+
+## Security Architecture
+
+Security is layered rather than monolithic. The important pieces live across `duh/kernel/`, `duh/tools/`, `duh/security/`, and `duh/adapters/sandbox/`.
+
+### 1. Taint Propagation
+
+`duh/kernel/untrusted.py` defines `UntrustedStr` and `TaintSource`. The goal is simple: keep track of where bytes came from so downstream policy can distinguish trusted operator intent from model/tool/network/file output.
+
+Taint enters the system in several places:
+
+- CLI prompt text is wrapped as `USER_INPUT` in `duh/cli/runner.py`.
+- REPL input is wrapped as `USER_INPUT` in `duh/cli/repl.py`.
+- SDK input is wrapped in `duh/cli/sdk_runner.py`.
+- file tools wrap data as `FILE_CONTENT`
+- network tools wrap data as `NETWORK`
+- native tool execution can wrap tool output as `TOOL_OUTPUT`
+- provider adapters and the stub provider wrap model text as `MODEL_OUTPUT`
+
+`UntrustedStr` overrides a large set of string-returning methods so taint usually propagates through concatenation, formatting, joins, case transforms, splits, and similar operations. The design is intentionally pragmatic, not formally complete. The module docstring explicitly calls out a limitation: multi-part f-strings can still drop taint because Python produces a plain `str` during formatting.
+
+### 2. Confirmation Tokens
+
+`duh/kernel/confirmation.py` provides `ConfirmationMinter`, which creates single-use, session-bound, tool-bound, input-bound HMAC tokens with a five-minute lifetime.
+
+`duh/security/policy.py:resolve_confirmation()` uses those tokens to block dangerous tool calls that originate from tainted context unless the operator explicitly confirms them.
+
+`duh/kernel/loop.py` already understands this gate: before a tool executes, it checks `deps.confirm_gate` and blocks if the decision says so. `Engine` also has `_check_confirmation_gate()` to connect session state and the per-session minter.
+
+One current tradeoff matters: the default `SessionBuilder` wires `approve`, `run_tool`, `compact`, hooks, and audit logging, but it does not currently set `Deps.confirm_gate`. So the confirmation-token architecture exists, the kernel supports it, and helper code mints tokens, but the default assembled session does not enable it yet. That is an important design seam and an honest current limitation.
+
+### 3. Approval Gates
+
+There are two approval layers:
+
+- tool-local permission checks via `tool.check_permissions()`
+- session-level approval adapters via `deps.approve`
+
+The built-in approval adapters in `duh/adapters/approvers.py` are:
+
+- `AutoApprover`
+- `InteractiveApprover`
+- `RuleApprover`
+- `TieredApprover`
+
+`TieredApprover` is the default safety model for REPL approval modes. It classifies tools into read, write, and command buckets using `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`, and it also contains a hard git safety check that blocks destructive git operations even in `FULL_AUTO`.
+
+### 4. Filesystem Boundaries
+
+`duh/security/path_policy.py` defines `PathPolicy`. `SessionBuilder` constructs it from the repo root, then passes it into file tools through `get_all_tools(...)`.
+
+Read/write/edit style tools resolve symlinks before policy checks, which is critical. Without that step, a symlink inside the repo could point outside the repo and bypass the boundary.
+
+### 5. Sandboxing
+
+The sandbox model is adapter-based:
+
+- `duh/adapters/sandbox/policy.py` defines `SandboxPolicy`, `SandboxType`, `detect_sandbox_type()`, and `SandboxCommand`.
+- `duh/adapters/sandbox/seatbelt.py` generates macOS profiles.
+- `duh/adapters/sandbox/landlock.py` builds Linux Landlock wrappers.
+
+`BashTool` consults `ToolContext.sandbox_policy`; if present, it wraps the command in a platform-appropriate sandbox before spawning the subprocess. MCP subprocesses use the same abstraction through `duh/adapters/mcp_executor.py`, which derives a sandbox policy from the MCP manifest.
+
+This layering matters: approval answers “may I run this?”, while sandboxing answers “if it runs, what can it touch?”.
+
+### 6. Session Capability Check: The Trifecta
+
+Before the session even starts, `Engine.__init__()` computes combined tool capabilities through `duh/security/trifecta.py`. If the session simultaneously enables:
+
+- `READ_PRIVATE`
+- `READ_UNTRUSTED`
+- `NETWORK_EGRESS`
+
+then `check_trifecta()` raises unless the operator explicitly acknowledges the risk via CLI flag or config. This is a startup-time exfiltration guard, not a per-call policy.
+
+### 7. Auditing and Redaction
+
+`duh/kernel/loop.py` emits tool audit records through `deps.audit_logger`. `SessionBuilder` wires `AuditLogger` by default in print mode assembly, and the CLI exposes audit output through `duh audit`.
+
+`duh/kernel/redact.py` provides secret redaction, and `NativeExecutor` can redact tool output before returning it to the kernel.
+
+## Threading and Concurrency Model
+
+D.U.H. is primarily an `asyncio` system. The default model is single-process, single-event-loop concurrency, with a few carefully chosen points of parallelism.
+
+### Turn Execution
+
+`Engine.run()` is an async generator. Every turn is streamed event by event. That makes the control flow easy to integrate in print mode, REPL, TUI, batch mode, and SDK mode without separate kernel variants.
+
+### Parallel Read-Only Tools
+
+Inside `duh/kernel/loop.py`, consecutive read-only tool calls are grouped and executed concurrently with `asyncio.create_task()` plus `asyncio.gather()`. Mutating tools always stay sequential.
+
+That gives D.U.H. limited speculative parallelism without risking write-order races. The grouping rule is intentionally strict:
+
+- read-only grouping depends on each tool’s `is_read_only`
+- result emission still happens in submission order
+- mutating tools preserve the exact assistant-requested order
+
+### Query Serialization
+
+`duh/kernel/query_guard.py` provides a generation-based state machine for callers that need to prevent overlapping queries. It supports both synchronous and async transitions and can optionally cancel the previous in-flight task when a new query is reserved.
+
+This is especially relevant for interactive frontends where a user can trigger another request before the last one finishes.
+
+### Background Jobs
+
+`duh/kernel/job_queue.py` provides a bounded async background queue used by `BashTool` for `bg:` commands. Jobs run under an `asyncio.Semaphore`, defaulting to five concurrent jobs, and completed results are retained up to a cap.
+
+### Persistence and File Safety
+
+`duh/adapters/file_store.py` uses atomic temp-file-then-rename writes, which gives safe local persistence without threads or a database. `UndoStack` and `FileTracker` are in-memory session helpers rather than concurrent shared services.
+
+## Known Tradeoffs
+
+### Centralized Session Assembly
+
+`SessionBuilder` is productive because it keeps one assembly path for print mode and REPL, but it is also heavy. Provider resolution, tool loading, config loading, MCP connection, prompt assembly, approver selection, and engine creation all happen in one class.
+
+The upside is coherence. The downside is a large file with many responsibilities.
+
+### Small Ports, Rich Adapters
+
+The ports are intentionally narrow, but that pushes complexity outward:
+
+- provider-specific streaming quirks live in adapters
+- tool capability classification lives outside the tool protocol
+- some safety behavior depends on both tool-local methods and external registries
+
+This is a deliberate bias toward a simple kernel at the cost of some manual wiring.
+
+### Security Is Layered, Not Formally Unified
+
+Taint tracking, approvals, confirmation tokens, path policy, sandboxes, audit logging, and trifecta checks are real, but they are not one single formally verified information-flow system. A contributor still needs to understand which layer they are relying on.
+
+The most notable current gap is the confirmation-token seam: supported by kernel and policy code, but not enabled by default in `SessionBuilder`.
+
+### Local-First Persistence
+
+Sessions, memory, and undo state are local-file oriented. That keeps the system easy to inspect and hack on, but it is not trying to be a distributed control plane, a multi-user service, or a transactional workflow database.
+
+### Explicit State Repair Over Hidden Magic
+
+Resume, compaction, and special modes are handled by explicit repair steps such as `restore_plan_context()`, `restore_skill_context()`, alternation repair in `validate_alternation()`, and session-mode restoration in `SessionBuilder._maybe_resume_session()`. That is more verbose than a framework-driven state machine, but it makes recovery behavior inspectable in ordinary Python files.
+
+### Manual Registries
+
+Adding a tool or slash command is straightforward, but it is not magically discoverable:
+
+- built-in tools go through `duh/tools/registry.py`
+- slash commands go through `duh/cli/slash_commands.py`
+- provider backends go through `duh/providers/registry.py`
+
+That is less dynamic than a plugin-first system, but it keeps the main runtime explicit and testable.
+
+## Non-Goals
+
+Several things are clearly not what this codebase is optimizing for:
+
+- It is not trying to hide control flow behind framework magic. Most important assembly is explicit Python.
+- It is not trying to make the kernel depend on provider SDKs or UI frameworks.
+- It is not trying to auto-parallelize arbitrary tool graphs; only a narrow read-only case is parallelized.
+- It is not trying to be a general workflow orchestrator or distributed task runner.
+- It is not trying to expose every internal extension seam as a polished plugin API yet.
+
+The resulting architecture is pragmatic: explicit wiring at the edges, a small async kernel in the middle, and safety mechanisms layered around tool execution rather than buried inside provider code.
