+# Tutorial: From Zero to Your First Custom Tool
+
+This walkthrough stays inside the pinned checkout and uses real symbols from the tree. It starts with installation, confirms the CLI works in stub mode, and then builds a custom tool end to end using the same kernel objects the product uses internally.
+
+Nothing here relies on invented helper APIs or pseudo-code wrappers.
+
+The examples assume:
+
+- you are in the repository root
+- you have Python 3.12 available
+- you want examples that work without a real API key
+
+Python 3.12 matters here because the codebase uses modern typing syntax such as `A | B`. If you accidentally run the examples with Python 3.9 or 3.10, imports from `duh/kernel/messages.py` will fail before you ever reach your custom tool.
+
+## 1. Install the Checkout
+
+Create or activate a Python 3.12 environment, then install the project in editable mode:
+
+```bash
+python3.12 -m pip install -e .
+```
+
+Expected output:
+
+```text
+Obtaining file:///.../codex-gpt54
+Installing collected packages: duh-cli
+Successfully installed duh-cli-0.8.0
+```
+
+The exact dependency lines will vary, but the important part is that `duh-cli` is installed from the current checkout.
+
+## 2. Hello World: Confirm the CLI Imports
+
+Before touching tools, confirm the package imports and the CLI entry point resolves:
+
+```bash
+python3.12 -m duh --version
+```
+
+Expected output:
+
+```text
+duh 0.8.0
+```
+
+That proves the Python package, `duh.__main__`, `duh.cli.main`, and `duh.cli.parser` all import cleanly.
+
+## 3. Run the Agent in Stub Mode
+
+The codebase ships a deterministic offline provider in `duh/adapters/stub_provider.py`. `duh/providers/registry.py` checks the `DUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1` environment variable before looking at any real provider credentials, so this is the fastest way to test the end-to-end CLI path.
+
+Run:
+
+```bash
+HOME="$PWD/.duh-home" DUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1 python3.12 -m duh -p "hello"
+```
+
+Expected output:
+
+```text
+WARNING: Detached HEAD — changes won't be on any branch
+WARNING: Uncommitted changes in working tree
+stub-ok
+```
+
+Those git warnings come from `duh/kernel/git_context.py`. The actual model response, `stub-ok`, comes from `StubProvider.stream()`.
+
+What just happened:
+
+1. `duh/cli/main.py` routed the request to `run_print_mode()`.
+2. `SessionBuilder` resolved the `"stub"` provider.
+3. The builder loaded the default tool set through `duh/tools/registry.py`.
+4. `Engine.run()` appended your prompt as a `Message`.
+5. `duh/kernel/loop.py:query()` called `StubProvider.stream()`.
+6. The runner rendered the streamed `text_delta`.
+
+That is the same control path as a real provider call, just without network traffic.
+
+## 4. Understand the Minimum Tool Surface
+
+The smallest useful custom tool only needs four things from `duh/kernel/tool.py`:
+
+- a `name`
+- a `description`
+- an `input_schema`
+- `async def call(self, input, context) -> ToolResult`
+
+You do not need to subclass anything. `duh/kernel/tool.py` defines `Tool` as a protocol, so any object with the expected shape works.
+
+The runtime pieces we will use are:
+
+- `ToolResult` and `ToolContext` from `duh/kernel/tool.py`
+- `NativeExecutor` from `duh/adapters/native_executor.py`
+- `Deps` from `duh/kernel/deps.py`
+- `Engine` and `EngineConfig` from `duh/kernel/engine.py`
+- an approver adapter from `duh/adapters/approvers.py`
+
+We also need a fake provider that actually asks for the tool. The stub provider is great for CLI smoke tests, but it only emits plain text; it never produces a tool-use block. So for the custom-tool demo, we will build a tiny in-process provider that emits a `tool_use` message on its first call and a final text response on its second call.
+
+## 5. Build a Custom Tool End to End
+
+Create a demo script in the repo root:
+
+```bash
+cat > hello_tool_demo.py <<'PY'
+import asyncio
+
+from duh.adapters.approvers import AutoApprover
+from duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor
+from duh.kernel.deps import Deps
+from duh.kernel.engine import Engine, EngineConfig
+from duh.kernel.messages import Message
+from duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult
+
+
+class HelloTool:
+    name = "Hello"
+    description = "Return a greeting."
+    input_schema = {
+        "type": "object",
+        "properties": {
+            "name": {"type": "string"},
+        },
+        "required": ["name"],
+        "additionalProperties": False,
+    }
+
+    @property
+    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:
+        return True
+
+    async def call(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:
+        return ToolResult(output=f"Hello, {input['name']}! cwd={context.cwd}")
+
+
+class DemoProvider:
+    def __init__(self) -> None:
+        self.calls = 0
+
+    async def stream(
+        self,
+        *,
+        messages,
+        system_prompt="",
+        model="",
+        tools=None,
+        thinking=None,
+        tool_choice=None,
+    ):
+        self.calls += 1
+        if self.calls == 1:
+            yield {
+                "type": "assistant",
+                "message": Message(
+                    role="assistant",
+                    content=[
+                        {
+                            "type": "tool_use",
+                            "id": "toolu_1",
+                            "name": "Hello",
+                            "input": {"name": "D.U.H."},
+                        }
+                    ],
+                    metadata={"stop_reason": "tool_use", "model": model or "demo-model"},
+                ),
+            }
+            return
+
+        tool_result = messages[-1].content[0]["content"]
+        text = f"Tool said: {tool_result}"
+        yield {"type": "text_delta", "text": text}
+        yield {
+            "type": "assistant",
+            "message": Message(
+                role="assistant",
+                content=[{"type": "text", "text": text}],
+                metadata={"stop_reason": "end_turn", "model": model or "demo-model"},
+            ),
+        }
+        yield {"type": "done", "stop_reason": "end_turn", "turns": 2}
+
+
+async def main() -> None:
+    tool = HelloTool()
+
+    executor = NativeExecutor(cwd=".")
+    executor.register(tool)
+
+    deps = Deps(
+        call_model=DemoProvider().stream,
+        run_tool=executor.run,
+        approve=AutoApprover().check,
+    )
+
+    engine = Engine(
+        deps=deps,
+        config=EngineConfig(
+            model="demo-model",
+            system_prompt="You are a demo.",
+            tools=[tool],
+            max_turns=4,
+            trifecta_acknowledged=True,
+        ),
+    )
+
+    async for event in engine.run("Say hello"):
+        if event["type"] in {"tool_use", "tool_result", "text_delta", "done"}:
+            print(event)
+
+
+asyncio.run(main())
+PY
+```
+
+Now run it:
+
+```bash
+python3.12 hello_tool_demo.py
+```
+
+Expected output:
+
+```text
+{'type': 'tool_use', 'id': 'toolu_1', 'name': 'Hello', 'input': {'name': 'D.U.H.'}}
+{'type': 'tool_result', 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_1', 'output': 'Hello, D.U.H.! cwd=.', 'is_error': False}
+{'type': 'text_delta', 'text': 'Tool said: Hello, D.U.H.! cwd=.'}
+{'type': 'done', 'stop_reason': 'end_turn', 'turns': 2}
+```
+
+That single file exercised the real kernel path:
+
+- `Engine.run()` created the session turn.
+- `query()` consumed the provider stream.
+- the provider emitted a real `tool_use` block embedded in a real `Message`.
+- `query()` called `deps.approve`.
+- `query()` called `deps.run_tool`.
+- `NativeExecutor.run()` built a real `ToolContext` and called your tool.
+- `query()` wrapped the tool output into a `tool_result_message`.
+- the provider saw the tool result in `messages[-1]` and produced final text.
+
+There are two deliberate design choices in that script:
+
+- `HelloTool` is just a plain Python object. It does not inherit from a framework base class, because the kernel consumes the structural `Tool` protocol from `duh/kernel/tool.py`.
+- `DemoProvider` is also just a compatible object with `stream(...)`. That mirrors how the real provider adapters are used: the kernel only cares that `Deps.call_model` yields the right event dictionaries.
+
+## 6. What Each Piece Does
+
+### The Schema
+
+Your tool’s `input_schema` is standard JSON Schema and is the same shape validated by `duh/kernel/schema_validator.py`. In built-in registration, `duh/tools/registry.py` validates schemas after tool construction and logs warnings for malformed schemas.
+
+For the demo tool:
+
+- `type: object` says the input must be an object
+- `properties.name` defines the argument
+- `required` makes `name` mandatory
+- `additionalProperties: False` keeps the contract tight
+
+### The Implementation
+
+The implementation surface is just:
+
+```python
+async def call(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult
+```
+
+`ToolContext` carries runtime state such as:
+
+- `cwd`
+- `session_id`
+- `tool_use_id`
+- `model`
+- `sandbox_policy`
+
+`ToolResult` carries:
+
+- `output`
+- `is_error`
+- `metadata`
+
+### Registration
+
+In the demo, registration happened here:
+
+```python
+executor = NativeExecutor(cwd=".")
+executor.register(tool)
+```
+
+That is real registration. `NativeExecutor` stores tools by `name`, and `query()` later resolves the tool call by name through `deps.run_tool`.
+
+There is a second registration path for product code: add the tool to `duh/tools/registry.py:get_all_tools()`. Use runtime registration for experiments and tests; use the registry when you want the CLI and REPL to load the tool automatically.
+
+## 7. Inspect the Engine State After the Run
+
+One useful property of `Engine` is that it keeps the whole conversation in memory, even when you drive it with a tiny custom provider. If you want to inspect that state after the run, replace the `async for` loop tail in `hello_tool_demo.py` with this:
+
+```python
+    async for event in engine.run("Say hello"):
+        if event["type"] in {"tool_use", "tool_result", "text_delta", "done"}:
+            print(event)
+
+    print("turns:", engine.turn_count)
+    print("messages:", len(engine.messages))
+    print("cost:", engine.cost_summary("demo-model"))
+```
+
+Expected output shape:
+
+```text
+{'type': 'tool_use', 'id': 'toolu_1', 'name': 'Hello', 'input': {'name': 'D.U.H.'}}
+{'type': 'tool_result', 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_1', 'output': 'Hello, D.U.H.! cwd=.', 'is_error': False}
+{'type': 'text_delta', 'text': 'Tool said: Hello, D.U.H.! cwd=.'}
+{'type': 'done', 'stop_reason': 'end_turn', 'turns': 2}
+turns: 1
+messages: 3
+cost: Input tokens: ...
+```
+
+The exact token and cost numbers depend on the model name you pass into `cost_summary()`, but the structure is stable:
+
+- one user message
+- one assistant message containing `tool_use`
+- one assistant text response after the tool result round-trip
+
+That is the same history shape the CLI stores through `FileStore`.
+
+## 8. Approval Policy: Why `AutoApprover` Was Used
+
+The demo uses `AutoApprover` on purpose. `TieredApprover` classifies tools using `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`, and your new tool is unknown until you add it there.
+
+Run this short check:
+
+```bash
+python3.12 - <<'PY'
+import asyncio
+
+from duh.adapters.approvers import ApprovalMode, TieredApprover
+
+
+async def main() -> None:
+    approver = TieredApprover(mode=ApprovalMode.SUGGEST, cwd=".")
+    print(await approver.check("Hello", {"name": "D.U.H."}))
+    print(await approver.check("Read", {"file_path": "README.md"}))
+    print(await approver.check("Write", {"file_path": "tmp.txt"}))
+
+
+asyncio.run(main())
+PY
+```
+
+Expected output:
+
+```text
+{'allowed': False, 'reason': "Unknown tool 'Hello' requires approval in suggest mode."}
+{'allowed': True}
+{'allowed': False, 'reason': "Tool 'Write' requires approval in suggest mode. Use --approval-mode auto-edit to auto-approve file edits."}
+```
+
+This is the rule to remember:
+
+- `is_read_only` affects concurrency in `duh/kernel/loop.py`
+- `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py` affects tiered approvals and snapshot blocking
+
+If you want your custom tool to behave like a built-in read tool under `TieredApprover`, you must classify it in `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`.
+
+## 9. Make the Tool a First-Class Built-In
+
+The demo script proved the kernel wiring. To ship the tool as part of D.U.H., follow the repo’s permanent registration path:
+
+1. Add `duh/tools/hello_tool.py` with the `HelloTool` class.
+2. Instantiate it from `duh/tools/registry.py:get_all_tools()`.
+3. If it should be treated as read-only, add `"Hello"` to `READ_TOOLS` in `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`.
+4. If it has session capabilities that matter for the trifecta check, set a `capabilities` flag on the tool class.
+5. If it needs repo-bound file access, accept a `path_policy` constructor argument like `ReadTool`, `WriteTool`, `EditTool`, and `MultiEditTool`.
+
+Those are all real files and real extension seams in this checkout. No extra plugin API is required for a built-in tool.
+
+One more practical note: built-in registration changes two separate surfaces.
+
+- `duh/tools/registry.py` controls whether the tool exists in the default session at all.
+- `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py` controls how approval modes and snapshot helpers reason about the tool.
+
+Skipping the second file is the most common mistake when moving from a demo script to a productized tool.
+
+## 10. Use the Same Pattern for Other Extensions
+
+The custom-tool path teaches most of the architecture:
+
+- Provider adapters plug in through `duh/ports/provider.py` and `duh/providers/registry.py`.
+- Slash commands plug in through `duh/cli/slash_commands.py`.
+- Kernel integrations flow through `Deps`, `EngineConfig`, and the event stream from `Engine.run()`.
+
+The key idea is always the same: keep the kernel talking to protocols and callables, then wire concrete behavior at the edges.
+
+In normal CLI sessions, that wiring is centralized in `duh/cli/session_builder.py`. That same builder is also where full sessions pick up:
+
+- skills from `duh/kernel/skill.py`
+- templates from `duh/kernel/templates.py`
+- MCP tool wrappers from `duh/adapters/mcp_executor.py` and `duh/tools/mcp_tool.py`
+- coordinator mode via the prompt path in `duh/kernel/coordinator.py`
+
+The custom-tool demo skipped those pieces so the runtime stayed minimal, but the extension seam is the same: explicit session assembly around `Deps`, `EngineConfig`, and the tool list.
+
+If you want to continue beyond tools, the next source files to read are:
+
+- `duh/ports/provider.py` and `duh/providers/registry.py` for a new provider adapter
+- `duh/cli/slash_commands.py` for a new slash command
+- `duh/cli/session_builder.py` if your extension needs to be loaded automatically in normal sessions
+
+That sequence matches how the runtime is assembled in the real CLI path.
+
+## 11. Troubleshooting
+
+### Import errors mentioning `|` in type hints
+
+You are not on Python 3.12. Re-run the commands with `python3.12`.
+
+### Your tool never runs
+
+Your provider did not emit a `tool_use` block. The stub provider is text-only, so it is good for CLI smoke tests but not for tool-invocation demos.
+
+### Your tool is denied in suggest mode
+
+That is expected for unknown tools under `TieredApprover`. Use `AutoApprover` while prototyping, or permanently classify the tool in `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`.
+
+### Your tool sees the wrong working directory
+
+`ToolContext.cwd` comes from `NativeExecutor(cwd=...)`. Set it deliberately if your tool depends on relative paths.
+
+### You added the tool to the registry but the CLI still will not auto-approve it
+
+Registry membership and approval classification are separate concerns. Add the tool name to the appropriate set in `duh/kernel/tool_categories.py`, or use a different approval adapter while you iterate.
+
+### You want to reuse the demo inside tests
+
+Keep the runtime-registration pattern. It is faster and more isolated than editing the built-in registry for every test fixture.
+
+## 12. What You Built
+
+By the end of this tutorial, you exercised the same core contracts D.U.H. uses in production:
+
+- `ToolContext` and `ToolResult` from `duh/kernel/tool.py`
+- `Deps` from `duh/kernel/deps.py`
+- `Engine` and `EngineConfig` from `duh/kernel/engine.py`
+- `NativeExecutor` from `duh/adapters/native_executor.py`
+- approval adapters from `duh/adapters/approvers.py`
+- kernel events flowing through `duh/kernel/loop.py`
+
+That is enough to build tools locally, embed D.U.H. into tests, or continue toward a built-in tool, a provider adapter, or a new slash command.
